{"id":"1807.03768","submitter":"Alexander Scott","authors":"Alex Scott and Paul Seymour","title":"Induced subgraphs of graphs with large chromatic number. XIII. New\n  brooms","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Gy\\'arf\\'as and Sumner independently conjectured that for every tree $T$, the\nclass of graphs not containing $T$ as an induced subgraph is $\\chi$-bounded,\nthat is, the chromatic numbers of graphs in this class are bounded above by a\nfunction of their clique numbers. This remains open for general trees $T$, but\nhas been proved for some particular trees. For $k\\ge 1$, let us say a broom of\nlength $k$ is a tree obtained from a $k$-edge path with ends $a,b$ by adding\nsome number of leaves adjacent to $b$, and we call $a$ its handle. A tree\nobtained from brooms of lengths $k_1,...,k_n$ by identifying their handles is a\n$(k_1,...,k_n)$-multibroom. Kierstead and Penrice proved that every\n$(1,...,1)$-multibroom $T$ satisfies the Gy\\'arf\\'as-Sumner conjecture, and\nKierstead and Zhu proved the same for $(2,...,2)$-multibrooms. In this paper\ngive a common generalization: we prove that every\n$(1,...,1,2,...,2)$-multibroom satisfies the Gy\\'arf\\'as-Sumner conjecture.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 10 Jul 2018 17:44:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-07-11"}
